But in the meantime, I’m just taking the time to travel ! In a little over a month, I’ve gone to 3 countries with limited time in between and as I always say, I’m nothing short of blessed!

Where to next? Who knows! But I want to go to one more country before the years up!

So help me out and let me know where it should be in the comments below!

After a month of training, learning the systems and automation of the Boeing 737 aircraft today was the big day!

Happy to announce that I passed my checkride and I’m officially Type Rated on the Boeing 737!

I couldn’t have asked for a better set of instructors and sim partner while training here at @americanair and the process was not only professional, but a really relaxing training environment where everyone wanted you to succeed.

I just want to thank GOD, my mother and father for always encouraging me and supporting me and never once had a doubt in my abilities. I love you dearly for all you have done throughout my life.

To my friends and family, thank you for your never ending support. Without you and the support and love, I don’t know where I’d be!

And to my followers! I thank you for the love and support as well, and I hope you see this as even more inspiration to aim high for your dreams and turn them into a reality.

Much love to you all!
#Pilot#Aviation#Avgeek#Airline#Flying#Travel#Thankful#Inspiration#BlackPilot

Today began the last first day of my career here at @americanair.

So part 1 of my full circle moment starts out of Dallas, Texas to my home state of New Jersey.

Landing just a few minutes up the road from my birthplace of Paterson, NJ into nearby Newark Airport, this was the same airport I first flew out of as a child that sparked my passion for aviation.

For my schedule to line up for me to fly my  first trip on my favorite aircraft (Boeing 737) that I grew up flying on as a child in my homestate is just a blessing.

As exciting as it is, it’s humbling as well to know the journey that it took me to get to this point.

My parents come from humble beginnings, coming from the tiny island of Jamaica, migrating to Canada, and eventually residing in New Jersey, their mission was to have a better life.

Their mission, flowed over with me, because with them raising me, they taught me the importance of hard work, the value of a dollar, and the reason for education.

All they ever wanted me to do was to succeed.

I never always listened, and some of my close friends know what I’ve been through and there were many times where I’ve failed and lived in times of uncertainty, but I kept pushing forward.

36 years later, I’m doing what I love and what ultimately I believe was destined to do and to come back to my HOME of New Jersey is such a blessing.

So Mom, Dad I thank you and love you for your constant support and love and for always pushing me to not be perfect, but to be my best.

To my loving friends and family and followers alike, I thank you for your support and this goes to show that anything is possible with the right attitude and mindset.

I did it yall.

So I’ll end this with a quote of mine…

“The sky’s not the limit when there’s footprints on the moon. And if they’ve made it that far,  you can shoot for the stars”

So as a pilot in reserve, one thing you learn not to do is make plans for your day.

What do I do? End up trying to make plans for my Sunday!

What ends up happening? I get called to do a ferry flight with a Maintenance team to  Mérida, Mexico to rescue passengers that were to fly back to Dallas, then swap planes to fix a downed bird with a flap malfunction.

Easy turn right? I was supposed to be back by 5pm!

Nope!The time to fix the aircraft would’ve taken the maintenance techs too long and we would’ve gone over our duty day so we cancelled and ended up staying.

Although it took us an hour to get to our overnight, as you can see , I think it was safe to say it was worth the drive to stay at an all inclusive  resort for 19 hours.

These are some of the scenarios you deal with as a pilot. Sometimes it works, sometimes it doesn’t but yesterday was one of those times it worked out!

If at first you don’t succeed…
Cars was my passion before flying.
For as long as I can remember as a toddler even I would always sit on the right seat looking at my father driving so I could look at the speedometer to see how fast my father would drive.

My first time into the car scene was 2001 Orlando Florida, I went to my first car meet at Sonics near international drive with my cousin Karsten and his friend Yeison. 

Yeison had a black 93 EG Hatchback with the big Tachmotor on the dash with a the red valve cover B18 motor in it with Nitrous in the rear trunk compartment. This was literally Fast n Furious before it came out a month or so after this meet.

I remember when he told me to twist the nitrous bottle open, and my GOD when he hit that button, it kinda really is like in the movies! 😂😂😂 it was the first car I was in that revved to 9500rpm. 

Years later I ended up owning 2 EG Hatchbacks like Yeison and had the pleasure of meetingup  @chrisguesttt one of my closest Jersey hometown friends to this day who ended up really got me situated in the Street Racing scene long before I became the law abiding responsible adult that I am today 😂😂😂

Now I’ve grown up, have some money in my pocket and have upgraded from Honda’s to Bimmers and had the pleasure to run my good friend @eva_clean_1  last night at @bradentonmotorsportspark. I’ll admit he’s faster than me and as you can see he got me in the first race, but I got my revenge and got my personal best time of 12.3 at 114mph last night!  This was my first time at an actual 1/4 mile track as well.

I was nothing short of excited and for the time money and dedication @miamiengines and @olympicmotorsports have spent on the car, I really appreciate it and couldn’t done it without their support.

So for all my BMW people here in SFLo make sure you check out @miamiengines whether it’s for an engine build or an oil change and speak to my man Luiggi over at @olympicmotorsports for all your tuning needs.They’ll get you right!

In the meantime enjoy the footage!

Welcome to Jamaica, the land that I love.

With some bonus takeoff footage from yours truly.

Although I wasn’t born in Jamaica, my entire family is and they come from humble beginnings. 

I might not of had to go walk miles and traverse through hills and valleys to go to school (As many Jamaican parents would make it seem and say 😂) I was most certainly still raised in a Jamaican household which was governed by the rod, the staff, a shoe, a belt and a switch from bush a time or two in my youth 😂

I have an overhwhelming amount of pride to represent the country my family  hails from because I know the hurdles they had to get through to be where they are today. 

They taught me the importance of hard work, the need for an education, and to work harder than I need to because you realize nothing in life comes easy nor is fair.

There’s always a smile on my face when I land here because I’m both happy and proud that the culture, the heritage, the lessons that have been passed on through the generations lives within me- mind, body and soul ,and it stems from one place, an Island they call Jamaica. 🇯🇲

It only took me 7 years to fill out the sleeves in my uniform shirt 😂

But hey I’m happy!

The road hasn’t been easy, I’ve had some weak moments, but thats  where the discipline comes in.

I made it a goal that after my checkride that I will  be healthy and fit for this summer and the summers in years to come and this has been the result of 5 months consistently training in the gym.

For the past 10 years I’ve been in and out the gym and it’s always been a bit difficult to stay consistent due to my career, but I made a choice to put forth as much energy and effort towards transforming my body. 

I have a long way to go, but with continued hard work and dedication I plan for even more growth for the summer.

So if anybody that’s been having a hard time getting into shape, the first step just getting yourself to the gym, so just do it!

The most exhilarating part of being an Airline Pilot for me has most definately got to be the takeoff.

To advance the throttles watch the N1’s spool up and hear the mighty roar of the CFM56’s thrust you into the vastness of the open air to climbout like a homesick Angel is one of the greatest experiences that will forever put a smile on my face.

Today I got to land in my home away from home, the country where my family is from the island of Jamaica.

I couldn’t of asked for better weather leaving today and I appreciate @mbjairportsltd for their constant professionalism and to one of the best Air Traffic Controllers in Jamaica @Aldane876 on the  amazing video footage of my departure out of Montego Bay.

Until next time Jamaica! I’m long overdue for a trip!

In the meantime watch me work! Enjoy the footage!

Fellas here’s a list of substance in regards to dating and first dates instead worrying if someone is judging you if you take them to the @cheesecakefactory instead of STK.

My rules, be financially responsible in regards to a first date. Don’t break the bank if you’re getting to know someone, but be the best you, the genuine you, and don’t put on an act.

So be confident.
That also means ( I know this is kinda hard for a lot of us) be vulnerable, but most importantly be the gentleman you would want your future daughter one day to marry.

And don’t sweat any woman that’s going to look down on you because you didn’t take them to the most expensive spot on the block. Know your WORTH and what YOU bring to the table.

Now ladies don’t be mad if the shoe fits.This isn’t a woman bashing post, this isn’t a victim shaming post.This is a post where both men and women can self reflect.If you feel a way about it, it might just mean you’ve got some areas of improvement and you LADIES can use this SAME list as well for your vettting process with men. I know more than anyone that I’m not perfect either, but if you want to make a list LADIES how about we try this for size? I promise you most men out here not trying to Mickey D their way to your heart with small fries.

The one thing I’ll always appreciate, is even though I was born and raised in the states, the embrace and acceptance and love I get from Jamaican nationals.

I feel good knowing that they’re truly happy that little ole me that comes from a family that comes from an Island that I hold dear to my heart.

But man she made my day and I most certainly made hers.

Finally I got to layover at the TWA Hotel!

As a child, the dream of becoming a pilot was something I never thought I would achieve, it was simply a dream. 

I came from a modest  American/Jamaican household as an only child, spent my first 4 or so years in private school, then I went to the public school system where I had a tough time all throughout my years. 

I never really interacted with my friends from school until high school as I was extremely sheltered and a very shy boy growing up.

But if there was one thing that would all me to open up it would be talking about my love for flying and airplanes.

I loved being at airports as a child.Always in awe of the hustle and bustle of the airline life. I always sat by the window seat and and always had a smile on my face from feeling the sheer power from the thrust of the jet engines.

Fast forward some years later, I remember when the movie “Catch Me If You Can” With Leonardo DiCaprio came out. At this point in my life, I still had no clue I would be eventually doing flight training a few years later. I was almost in a point in my life where I felt defeated. 

Renting a room, being away from my parents, working 6 days straight. With 2, sometimes 3 jobs, I was just trying to make ends meet for myself.

But for those who haven’t seen the movie, I think it captured and depicted the “Golden Years” of the age of airline flying back in the 60’s quite well although I wasn’t around to witness it.

Throughout the years I’ve heard many tales from many retired pilots and pilots that have since gone west on how the  airline life used to be.

Coming to the TWA hotel was one of the most unique airline experiences yet. With an entirely whole “Sixties” feel to it.
To walk through with my neatly pressed uniform on, cleanly shaved, and see adults walk past me and smile and kids look up in awe it felt like a scene out the movie!

That’s why I go into work thankful and humbled, because I know where I came from and it’s always been a blessing to be where I am today.

Sometimes I feel like I’m in a movie, but I’m just living the dream.
